Chess Playback

We at Endava like playing chess. We also like to go back to some of the games and analyze them, so we can learn from our mistakes. Your job for this current assignment is to create a react application which receives chess games data from a backend API and visualizes the games. There should be several controls for navigating in the particular game. But as they say, a GIF is worth 1000 words:

The chess-playback folder is where you will write your code. In there, currently there is a folder called backend where the NodeJS API for getting the games data lives. In order to run the API, go to the backend folder and run npm install. Then you can start the API with npm start. For your assignment (writing the frontend) you can use create-react-app or any other tool to help you bootstrap your initial react application. You can make a folder called frontend and put the react application there.

Requirements

  • On initial loading of the app, a request should be made to the API endpoint - http:://localhost:8080/games in order to get the games data
  • On the left hand side there should be a menu with the different games, similar to the image above. By clicking a menu item the game is loaded on the right hand side.
  • In the main window, there is a title on the top, with the two players of the game.
  • The result of the game is shown below (i.e. Result: 0-1)
  • The date on which the game is played is shown.
  • Below this, is the section with all the moves.
  • List all the moves for the selected game. There should be some sort of separation between the different moves, similar to the image above. (i.e. 1. c4 - e5; 3. Nc3 - Nc6; etc...)
  • Below this is the actual chess board, which initially is set to the starting position
  • Below the board there are three buttons - Play, Next and Reset
  • By clicking Play the game is started and every next move is made in 1 second interval. The text of the button changes to Stop. Clicking Stop stops the playback of the game at the current position.
  • Clicking Next makes the next move in the game. The Next button should be disabled, while the Play button is on.
  • Clicking the Reset button resets the game to the initial position

Hints

  • As making the board from scratch would be a big effort we recommend using chessboardjsx which is a react component for visualizing a chess board. You can use any third party library you like, but this one was really simple to use.
  • Your final version of the app should look something similar to the image above, although don't focus on the styles too much. Make only the layout similar to the image.
  • Explanation of the response from /games endpoint:
  • The /games endpoint returns an array of game objects. Each game object has several properties.
  • The properties white and black contain the names of the two players.
  • The date property contains the date of the game.
  • The result property is for the final result of the game. (i.e. 0-1 this means that the player with the black pieces won)
  • The moves property is an array with all the moves in the game. Use it for showing the moves in the moves section of the app.
  • The fens property is an array of FEN strings. A FEN string is a notation used in computer chess games. Each FEN string is the current representation of the board after every move. Pass the FEN strings for the different moves to the chessboardjsx component so the current representation of the board can be shown. (more info here)
  • Regarding additional third party libraries, you can use whatever you like, the only requirement is using reactjs
  • For state management you are free to use whatever you prefer, component state, hooks, redux etc...

Bonus points. These additional things are not mandatory but will be looked upon with admiration. Only do these if you have time and feel like it.

  • Add unit or integration tests.
  • Using any kind of component or CSS library (bootstrap, materialUI etc...)
  • Any additional functionality that you think would be cool to add to this app.

Handover

Even if you haven't completed all of the requirements, send it anyway and we'll take a look.

When you feel you're ready with the assignment, delete the node_modules folders in both the backend and frontend folders, zip them, and send the archive.

If you have any questions please don't hesitate to ask us!

Hope you enjoy building this app and good luck!
